Developing Data Products: Shiny Video Game Review Analysis

Tony Matera
November 5, 2016

IGN Video Game Reviews

For years, IGN has been reviewing video games and used to be a trusted source for whether a video game was worth buying. However, they have been scrutinized for possibly becoming biased over the years, perhaps being incentivized to give certain games greater scores than otherwise deserved.

This Shiny-based app allows users to begin to look for hard evidence of biased reviews based on this data, which consists of all game review scores scraped from the IGN website by Reddit user /u/CDanger.

The data consists of four fields:

  • Game - the name of the video game
  • Platform - the gaming system upon which the game was reviewed
  • Score - IGN's game review score
  • Genre - genre of the game

To preserve simplicity within the app, the data used includes only the most popular gaming systems of the past twenty years.

App Layout and Instructions


Here is a screenshot of what you see when you first open the application:




  • Filter by Platform and/or by Genre by checking/unchecking the appropriate boxes.
  • Click the All/Random buttons to select all platforms/genres (if not all are selected) or select a random one (if all are selected)
  • Filters also apply to the Data Table to reference which games are showing up after filtering
  • Below each plot is a summary of scores by Platform/Genre
